Data aggragation and summarization

# install.packages("dplyr")
#library(dplyr)
df <- data.frame(
  Group = c("A", "A", "B", "B", "A", "B"),
  Value = c(10, 20, 15, 25, 30, 35)
)

grouped_df <- df %>% group_by(Group) %>% summarize(Mean_Value = mean(Value))
print(grouped_df)

Data transformation

#install.packages("tidyr")
# library(tidyr)
wide_df <- data.frame(
  ID = c(1, 2),
  Jan = c(100, 150),
  Feb = c(120, 160),
  Mar = c(130, 170)
)

long_df <- pivot_longer(wide_df, cols = -ID, names_to = "Month", values_to = "Value")
print(long_df)

Data visualization in R

Introduction to ggplot2 for data visualization

#install.packages("ggplot2")
# library(ggplot2)
df <- data.frame(
  Category = c("A", "B", "C"),
  Value = c(10, 20, 15)
)

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = Category, y = Value)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

df <- data.frame(
  X = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5),
  Y = c(10, 20, 15, 25, 30)
)

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = X, y = Y)) +
  geom_point()

df <- data.frame(
  X = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5),
  Y = c(10, 20, 15, 25, 30)
)

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = X, y = Y, color = "My Data Points")) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot Example", x = "X Axis", y = "Y Axis") +
  theme_minimal()

df <- data.frame(
  Category = rep(c("A", "B"), each = 5),
  Value = c(10, 20, 15, 25, 30)
)

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = Category, y = Value)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  facet_wrap(~ Category)

T-Test

# Creating df with info for males and females
female_df <- csv_data %>% filter(sex == "F")
male_df <- csv_data %>% filter(sex == "M")

female_df
male_df
height_F <- female_df$height
height_M <- male_df$height

# Perform independent t-test
t_test_result <- t.test(height_F, height_M)
print(t_test_result)

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  height_F and height_M
t = -0.20625, df = 1.13, p-value = 0.8674
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -322.574  309.174
sample estimates:
mean of x mean of y 
    159.8     166.5

p-value = 0.8674 p-value > 0.05, cela signifie qu’il n’y a pas de différence statistiquement significative entre la taille des hommes et des femmes

csv_data

blue is 0 green is 1 brown is 2 For practical reasons (just to see how the test works), we modified the categorical variables into numeric.

csv_data$eye_color[csv_data$eye_color =="blue"] <- 0
csv_data$eye_color[csv_data$eye_color =="green"] <- 1
csv_data$eye_color[csv_data$eye_color =="brown"] <- 2
